        output='Based on a review of the provided S-1 filing excerpts, here is the information you requested:\n\n### 1. Economic Rights of Class A vs. Class B Common Stock\n**Yes, they have identical economic rights.**\n\nMultiple sections of the prospectus explicitly state that the three classes of common stock (A, B, and C) share the same economic rights with respect to dividends and liquidation. The key passages are:\n\n*   **Dividends:** "Any dividends paid to the holders of shares of Class A common stock, Class B common stock and Class C common stock will be paid pro rata, on an equal priority, pari passu basis."\n*   **Liquidation:** Upon liquidation, "holders of shares of Class A common stock, Class B common stock and Class C common stock are entitled to share ratably in all assets remaining after payment of liabilities and the liquidation preference of any then outstanding shares of capital stock."\n*   **Earnings Per Share:** The accounting note confirms "the Company’s classes of common stock have identical economic rights, resulting in the same net income (loss) per share for each class. Accordingly, the Company presents a single net income (loss) per share for all classes of common stock."\n\n**The primary difference is in voting rights**, not economics:\n*   **Class A Common Stock:** 1 vote per share.\n*   **Class B Common Stock:** 10 votes per share. Additionally, Class B shareholders, voting as a separate class, are entitled to elect 51% of the board of directors.\n*   **Class B Conversion:** Each share of Class B is convertible at any time into one share of Class A. It also converts automatically upon any transfer (except for certain "Permitted Transfers").\n\n### 2. Pro Forma Adjusted Share Count & Calculation Framework\nThe filing provides a **clear framework** for calculating the post-IPO fully diluted share count, though the final "Pro Forma as Adjusted" numbers are intentionally left blank (represented by "%") as they depend on the final offering price and size.\n\n**Framework from the Capitalization Table and Footnotes:**\n\n1.  **Actual (Pre-IPO) Share Counts (as of March 31, 2026):**\n    *   Class A: 2,964,501,353 shares issued; 2,882,444,444 shares outstanding.\n    *   Class B: 2,421,276,530 shares issued and outstanding.\n    *   Class C: 494,026,445 shares issued and outstanding.\n    *   Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock: 189,155,861 shares issued; 134,451,267 shares outstanding.\n\n2.  **Key Adjustments for "Pro Forma" (Pre-IPO, Structural Changes):**\n    The "Pro Forma" column reflects these corporate actions as if they had already occurred:\n    *   **Preferred Conversion:** All outstanding shares of Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock convert into Class A Common Stock.\n    *   **Class C Reclassification:** Shares of Class C Common Stock are reclassified (likely into Class A).\n    *   **Stock Split:** A 10-for-1 stock split (referred to as "2026 Stock Split") is applied.\n    *   **Charter Effectiveness:** The new corporate charter, which establishes the authorized share counts, becomes effective.\n\n    *Result (Pro Forma):*\n    *   Class A: 6,824,581,339 shares issued and outstanding.\n    *   Class B: 5,695,729,430 shares issued and outstanding.\n    *   Class C: 0 shares issued and outstanding.\n\n3.  **"Pro Forma as Adjusted" Calculation (Post-IPO):**\n    This layer adds the IPO itself to the Pro Forma capitalization:\n    *   **IPO Shares Sold:** The sale of new Class A Common Stock by the company.\n    *   **Underwriters\' Option:** The potential sale of additional Class A shares (typically 15% of the offering) if the overallotment option is exercised.\n\n    *Calculation Framework Provided:*\n    *   The filing explains that the "Pro Forma as Adjusted" columns assume the IPO price is at the midpoint of the price range and apply the net proceeds.\n    *   It provides a sensitivity analysis: "If the initial public offering price were to increase or decrease by $1.00 per share... if the number of shares of Class A common stock offered by us were to increase or decrease by [shares]..."\n    *   The **Beneficial Ownership table footnote** explicitly outlines the calculation method: Post-offering ownership percentages are based on the total of (Pro Forma Class A shares) + (Class A shares sold in the IPO) and the Pro Forma Class B shares.\n\n**Summary of the Calculation Path:**\n```\nActual Pre-IPO Shares\n         ↓\n[Apply: Preferred Conversion, Class C Reclassification, 10-for-1 Stock Split]\n         ↓\n"Pro Forma" Shares (Reflects structural changes only)\n         ↓\n[Add: Shares sold in IPO (primary + overallotment option)]\n         ↓\n"Pro Forma as Adjusted" Shares (Reflects post-IPO capitalization)\n```\n\nIn conclusion, while the final numeric "Pro Forma as Adjusted" share counts and voting power percentages are blank (awaiting the final IPO price and size), the filing provides a complete and specific operational framework for calculating them once those variables are known.',
